results.occurrenceRemarks: During a group visit to the giraffes (Giraffa camelopardalis perlata) at Koure, about 60 km ESE of Niamey on highway N1, we saw a total of 33 individuals during a period of a little over 2 hours, all within a 5 km radius of the guides center on the north side of the highway. Two family groups, and several smaller groups of juveniles were observed, along with some interesting behaviour. One male, with a large harem of four adult females and six juveniles (2 born this past year, and four older juveniles), successfully defended the territory of his group by charging after a passing smaller male/female/juvenile group, chasing it away, and then charging off in the other direction later when the intruders tried to circle around behind the larger group. The adult male and female in the smaller group indulged in a bit of "necking" (swinging their heads down with the apparent intention of hitting their opponent in the rump or side with their horns), and pushing each other around. They stopped this activity only when a bullock cart approached, which they showed considerable interest in. Several of the observed individuals approached to less than 50 m the observers, apparently curious to get a closer look the oberservers themselves. Photos of 15 different individuals are provided. This is apparently the last remaining wild population of giraffes in West Africa, and is growing rapidly following a dip to less than 60 individuals some 20 years ago. The total number in the population last year was 193, and as evidenced by the large proportion of juveniles and recently born among the animals that we observed, it is increasing rapidly.
